Domitian laid a heavy poll-tax on this people3 and, that they might not erade it, they were enjoined not to appear abroad without the basket and hay, the badges of their condition. To avoid being de- tected and insulted by the rabble when they entered the city, these poor perse- cuted wretches laid aside their degrading accompaniments. This accounts for the epithet tremens, which Juvenal applies to the female fortune-teller3 who, ifshe had been discovered, would, in spite of her lofty pretensions, have been severely punished for contempt of the imperial regulations.
